window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>1","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION A - FACELESS - AMMA DARKO    Explain Kabria's presence in the hairdressing salon at Agbogboshie.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Agbogbloshire Market is where Kabira shops for her vegetables. On the Monday following the discovery of Baby T's body behind a hairdressing salon, she and Fofo get acquinted under curious circumstance. Disguised as a boy, Fofo attempts to steal Kabira's purse.    Kabria is moved to rescue the 'boy' as a matter of conscience when 'he' is about to lynched by the crowd that apprehend 'him'.   Later at the office of MUTE, the foursome officials- Dina,Vickle, Aggie and Kabira, discuss Fofo and Baby T and reach a concensus that Kabria ought to honour her appointment with Fofo at the Agbogbloshire Market in order to get to the bottom of the death of Baby T and Fofo's predicaments.    All of the above scenarios trigger Kabira's visit to the hairdressing Salon. Kabria therefore goes to the salon at Agbogbloshire not to have her hair done, but to primarily conduct investigation to unravel the mystry surrounding the death of Baby T. Therefore, Kabria's presence in the hairdresser salon is purely in her private capacity as an investigative reporter'.        Unfortunately for Kabira, her visit to the salon is initially a disappointment. She is unable to obtain information of any substance from the hairdresser. She is tense: **\"To tell you the truth, my sister, what at all am I suppossed to know?, and she shrugs. Actually i didnt come to meet the body\". Instead of information about the dead girl behind her salon, the hairdresser pours out fustration about her broken marriage, which has saddled her with responsibility to cater for the children of a runaway husband, Kabira wins her Sympathy after telling her worse situation in her own marriage. She then directs her (Kabira) to see her own senior apprentice for some details about the dead girl.    Kabira approaches the hairdresser's senior appretice who makes the interesting revelations. It appears Baby T is killed somewhere else and the Kayoyoos say Baby T is not one of them. Three days after the corpse is dumped near the Kiosk, pacification rites are performed at the spot by unknown persons. These, among others, leave more questions unanswered on Kabra's mind.    This, however, gingers Kabria and her colleagues into more actions. Eventually, Kabria's presence at the hairdressing salon leads to a host of investigative activities that trace the murder of Baby T to the door step of Poison and Onko.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>2","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION A - FACELESS - AMMA DARKO Comment on the significance of Sodom and Gomorrah","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Sodom and Gomorrah is the seat of the various foms of evil of the various forms of evil in the world of Faceless. It is that part of the citu where people can be said to be faceless and without an identity. It is home for hardened thieves, prostitutes and children driven from home or ones without a home. It is an area that is covered in filth and sqealor. A the same implies, the place that breeds all sort of evil in the children who live there. Fofo, ordarley and the other do not leave home already depraved. it is the life at Sodom and Gomorrah that makes them so.    The going-ons in Sodom and Gomorrah are debashing. The best word to describe the morality of Sodom and Gomorrah is \"depraved\".The habits of the juveuile inhabitants who engage in acts of debauchery by \"drinking bottle of akpeteshire and watching adults films\" are deplorable. Youngsters steal and engage in prostitution fora living in the evil enviroment. Bullies like poison and Macho terrorize the children, deprive them of their money and even attempt to, and do rape the young helpless girls. There is no way of ptotecting these vulnerable young people. The early mention of Sodom and Gomorrah in the novel establishes its significance. It is a phenomenon that has   \"catapulted from the pages of old testament to super impose itself at Agbogbloshire\"    Sodom and Gomorrah is significant in a number of ways. When Kabira goes \"to visit Agbogbloshire market for some garden eggs and tomatoes\", she meets a petty thief from sodom and Gomorrah, who picks her purse. She saves the life of the pick-pocket who would have been subjected to instant mob justuce (lynching).    Anotther aspect of Soldom and Gomorrah which is significant is its sustenance by those who profit from it. The coming of children into the streets and their living in Sodom and Gomorrah appear unstoppable. This is because of the activities of the likes of Maami Broni and Poison. Sodom and Gomorrah depicts the helplessness of the situation of children who are driven into the streets and have no prospects for the future. As the children are driven into the street, there are ready recievers who ensure that they stay, and they supervise their abuse. Sodom and Gomorrah is also significant in as far as no steps seem to be taken by the powers of that be to intervene. Sodomand Gomorrah cries for cleansing but the state machinery does not hear or seem to care. The police are sileint about,and invisible in, the affairs of the street children. No actions is taken when crimes ar reported to the police .    But for Kabira's encounter with Fofo, the NGO MUTE, would not have come to the rescue of the girl. The support of Harvest FM gives impetus to the MUTE effort. The question, as to whether this single intervention of the non-governmnetal organisation is all there and can be and whether it suffices, require critical answers. The enquires about the murdered girl found in the gutter recieve lukeworm attention from the police.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>3","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION A - LONELY DAYS - BAYO ADEBOWALE    \"No woman's life is ever complete without a man.\" How is this applicable to Yaremi in the novel.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Yaremi, a beautiful widow in her early fifties in Kufi, has recently lost her husband, Ajumobi. Their children, all grown up including Alani the only son, have left home.  Women In Kufi, by tradition, are only considered complete when they ar part of a couple,even if they are the second or third wife. In the unfortunate event of the death of a husband, a woman is expected to remarry.  Yaremi, being the strong-willed woman she is, decides against re-marriage to any of the available suitors. Nine months after ther death of her husband, Yaremi is still without another husband, to thr changrin of the men in Kufi, who she tells she is \"neither a napkin or a rag to clean up mess with\". Hence, she rejects all the caps of the three suitors who wants to mary her.  With that firlmy established, she then directs her energy towards filling the void left by Ajumobi's death. She decides to work hard, doing manual jobs to fill in the long hours of her lonely days under the hot sun. She does the farm work , cleans the family compound, dries the maize, grains, uproots cassava tubers for the goats, cocks, fetches water and firewood and does other household chores alongside her main jobs for which she requests assistance from the villiage men like uncle Dayo. She still needs her husband to eat the food she prepare. She also needs, she realises, a husband to eliminate the termites,red ants, and rats around the home,  Yaremi also longs for husband's touch and his deep manly voice. In her loneliness, she dreams about him often, and imagines he has come to visit her. She misses their quarrels and prays for him to return as it is impossible for to forget certain events.  She tells Segi: \" Your father was to me like the mighty Baobab, king of savannah, towering above ten thousand lesser trees around, protecting me under its cool shade.... But death was so cruel. It came like harmattan blaze to strip my only dress, my Baobab, leaving me to stand alone in mournful nakedness  Thus, despite Yaremi's determination tostand aganist tradition in her refusal to remarry, she realises that desirability of being part of a couple,as long as her husband is Ajumobi.","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>4","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"","topic":"AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION A - LONELY DAYS - BAYO ADEBOWALE Examine the author's narrative technique in the novel","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The author tells his story from the third person point of view. With this omniscient perspective, he demonstrates his skill in observing people and events very closing and passing comments on them.  One remarkable feature of the author's technique is his drawing very deeply from the African oral tradition in his narative. This is often overreaches itself in his own wiles and cunning, the antelope that often falls on its own pride and gluttonous baboon that dies from its rapacious greed. There is also the use of incantation as shown by both Ajumobi and Yaremi to neutralise the evil machinations of their percieved enemies.  The author employs flashbacks as Yaremi,on a good number of occassions, recalls the halcyons days with her late husband and eulogises his sterling qualities as a husband and his prowess as a hunter.  Another feature employed in the narration is dialogue. Instances are the exchanges between Yaremi and woye, Yaremi and Ajumobi, Yaremi and her suitors, the widows on their way to the river, etc.  Indeed, the use of figurative language permeates the entire work. Refernces can be made to the cap-picking ceremony where the suitors' personalities, etc., are delineated.  Also significant is the use of words or expression drawn from the local language. often, these put emphasis on tradition and folklore, thereby adding colour to the setting. There is also the use of traditional songs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>5","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"5","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION B - NATIVE SON - RICHARD WRIGHT    Discuss the role of the black clergy in the novel","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Rev Hammond is a black dergyman of Bigger's Mother's church.    He visits Bigger in his cell. As soon as Bigger recognises him, he is on guard against him. Bigger fears pastors make him feel remorseful and wants to tell him to go out but cannot speak.    Reverend Hommond kneels on the concrete floors to pray for the salvation of bigger's soul. He repeatedly refers to bigger as a \"poor boy\", seeing Bigger as a sinner who needs salvation. As the words of the pastor's prayer register themselves in Bigger's conciousness, they make him remember his mother's voice telling of suffering, hope and love beyond the world. this makes bigger feel condemned and guilty.    Bigger hates the Clergyman's creed and wishes he will stop praying. He cannot repeat any of the preacher words, but they make him (Bigger) feel like leaping up strike him. Before he leaves , Reverend Hammond gives Bigger a wooden cross, trying to make him believe that life is all suffering. This, Bigger rejects in his heart.    The visit and prayer of the black clergyman expose the hyprocritical attitude of the black church and its attitude of Capitulating to the situation of its members. It is ironical that the church cannot even engage the services of lawyer for Bigger, which is what he needs at this time. This Reverend Hammond knows as he tells Jan that if any body needs help, then Bigger does.    The clergy contrast, Jan, not only in race and Occupation, but in his beliefe in what man needs in life. Jan forgives Bigger and engages a lawyer to defend him now. But Reverend Hammond thinks of the hereafter. Bigger's case needs prompt and immediate attention, but the clergyman offers freedom of the soul, whilst Jan offers immediate and prompt attention.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>6","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION B - NATIVE SON - RICHARD WRIGHT What have you learned about black life from the conversation between Bigger and Gus at the entrance to the pool room?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Bigger leaves home that fateful morning to avoid his mother's incessant nagging about the family's poor living condition and he is not able to be of any help. She warns him against his continued involvement with the gang and prophesises doom for him if he disregards his warning. He heads for the pool room where he feels more at ease. He meets Gus, a member of the gang at the entrance and they drift into a conversation.     Their conversation reveals much about the living conditions of the black people. It exposes their forced segregated lives, their exclusion from participation in the political, militatry and commercial life of white America, as well as their bottled up fudtration which stir up anger in some of them    We learn, for instance, that blacks live under very poor conditions. Bigger and Gus observe and appreciate natures i.e, the warm day, both reflect on the poor heating system in their homes. Though their landlords 'dont give much heat, they always demand rent'.    They reflect also on the segregated lives, which bother a lot, Bigger observe that whites live \"over across the line, over there on, cottage grove avenue\". Explaining the source of their bitterness, he intone:\" we live here, and they live there, we black and they are white. They get things and we aint. They do things and we cant . Account for his feelings, he says, \" I feel like I'm not outside of the World peeping in through a knot-hole in the fence.    Bigger and cavs refers also to the power structure in American Society, from the presidency to the military, business and commerce.  Their simulations of a telephone conversation between the president of the United states and his secretary of the state on the one hand, and J.P Morgan, a business mogul and someone else is also revealing. It is revealed that the president's secretary of State is more ready  to attend a Cabinet meeting about \" the niggers rising send all over the country\" than one Involving Germans. And J.P Morgan is prepared to sell twenty thousand shares of U.S steel, a mind-boggling figure. That kind of business transaction is way beyond blacks to do. These shows the extent to which whites suppress to put blacks in their places.    Blacks are also prevented from aspiring to do anything worthwhile, \"They get the chance to do anything\", but \" They dont let us do anything.\" Whereas the whites, like the pigeons, can go wherever they want, the blacks are restricted in their movements.    The conversation reveals two contrasting attitude of the blacks towards their situation in the novel. Some blacks, like Gus, are resigned to their fate. Others, like Bigger, breed anger in themselves against the system.    Thus, the conversation gives a microscopic view of black life in the novel.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>7","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"7","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION B - THE CASTLE OF OTRANTO - HORACE WALPOLE    Comment on the significance of Conrad's death in the novel","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Conrad's death is significant both in its contribution to plot development and also to character delineation.    Conrad, son and heir of Manfred, dies when he is mysteriously crushed by a gigantic stone helmet. He does not really appear as a character in the novel but is very important and his death has a direct influence on the major actions in the novel.    Conrad is supposed to many Isabella, daughter of Federic. Fedrick is in actual fact, the real heir to the castle of Otranto. Manfred arranges the marriage between Conrad and Isabella in other to unite the two factions claiming rights to Otranto. Conrad's death put's paid to Manifred's attempt to consolidate his own position through his son. Thus he turns his attention to other means to attain his goal. This sets into motion a chain of events which culminate in his downfall and the restoration of the castle of Otranto to Theodore who is decleared as the true heir of the castle. The prophecy that the castle will be restored to its rightful heir \" Whenever the owner should be grown two large to inhabit it\" it thus fulfilled.    Isabella's repugnance at the Idea of her marrying Manfred, after his proposed divorce of his wife, Hippolita, leads her to run away from the castle to the church of St. Nicholas, to seek the protection of Friar Jerome. This action is in itself significant since it brings the holy father into direct conflict with Manfred to sin futher by challenging the spiritual powers.    Conrad's death also introduces Theodore into the actions of the novel. Theodore's explanation on discovery of the dead Conrad generates a conflict between him and Manfred. Theodore's alliance with Isabella complicates the novel's plot further. Manfred mistakenly believes that the two are in love much to his annoyance as he regards it as an affront to his authority. This stage is therefore set for the final confrotation in the novel which results in Manfred's downfall and the return of the return of the castle of Otranto to its rightful heir.    Conrad's death also contributes to the delineation of Manfred's character. It exposes Manfred's depravity and his capacity for evil machinations. Conrad's death leaves him with only one option as he sees it to consolodate his hold on the castle. When his attempt to obtain Isabella's consent to marry him by lechery and subterfuge fails, he resorts to violence. His lechery and unscrupulousness are accentuated by Conrad's removal from the scene and he is esposed for what he really is. With the Introduction of Theodore immediately after Conrad's death, a formidable opponent to Manfred's evil plans emerges.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper II>8","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"8","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN PROSE","question":"SECTION B - THE CASTLE OF OTRANTO - HORACE WALPOLE Examine the relationship between Manfred and Hippolita.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Manfred, the prince of Otranto, is married to Hippolita, a body he later points out to be a distant relation of his.    They have two children, Matilda, Their eightteen-year-old daughter and Conrad, their fifteen-year-old son.    Hippolita is described as \"an amiable lady\" and is presented in the novel as a subservient wife who treats her husband with outmost respect. Her love for her husband is not reciprocated. This is so because Manfred's attitude towards her is one of utter disdain, though he himself says of her, \"true, I honour Hippolita's virtue, I think her a saint.......\"    In the first place, he does not take her suggestions into consideration. When Manfred's hatches plot  the marriage between conrad and Isabella, Hippolita calls his attention to the fact that Conrad, their ailing son, is too young to marry.Manfred responds  by blaming her Inability to give him more than one heir. The marriage plan ends disastrously with the mysterious death of Conrad on the wedding day.     Manfred's Inhuman treatment of his wife only intensifies after Conrad's death. Hippolita, on recovering from the initial shock at the news demands regular updates on her 'Lord' the way she refers to Manfred, on the other hand, doesnot even mention his wife or daughters, as the first words he utters to the ladies in the chapel after the incident are;\" Take care of the Lady Isabella\" Hippolita sends matilda,their daughter to see how Malfred  is coping with his loss. When Maltilda attempts to do so, she cannot find words to explain to her mother ' reception she has recieved from her father, on her return to Hippolita.    Hippolita, on her part, registers her disappointment that manfred has not reguested to see her when she says mournful; \"But will he permit  me to blend my tears with his, and shed a mother's sorrow in the bossom of her Lord\".    She is also worried that Conrad's tragic death must have affected manfred very badly and demands that she be taken to see him, when says to her maids;\" Raise me , my maidens; i will see my Lord. Bear me to him instantly; He is clearer to me than my children.    It is heart-rending that manfred does not cave or ask to see his wife but sends to summon Isabella instead. Hippolita, in innocence, thinks that manfred is apprehensive of meeting herself  and maltilda and that is why he chooses to send for Isabella instead. She tells Isabella, \"console him, dear Isabella and tell him i will smother my own anguish rather than add to his\"    This is contrary to an ideal marriage relationship situation where, at least, both the husband and wife show concern each  other. little does Hippolite knows that Manfred is desirous to propose to Isabella. She trust her husband very much.    When Isabella, on hearing the proposal fleas the castle, Manfreds Footsteps on the stairs, Hippolita hastly goes out auxious to meet him for the first time after son's death. He pushes her \" rudely off\" demanding to know Isabella's whereabouts and even mentions Hippolita is jealous of Isabella. Hippolita, through surprised at this uterances being the obedient wife she is, carries out manfred's order to send her chaplain to him. Hippolita later tells Manfred that the 'gigantic leg' is just a figment of the imagination. Manfred is relieved but his attitude towards his wife does not improve; infact, it get worse.    Relaying on Hippolita's submissiveness, manfred plots to divorce her and marry isabella. When friar Jerome comes with the information on Isabella. Manfred sees the opportunity to get into dissolve his marriage to Hippolita so he could marry Isabella his once proposed daughter in law. When he insists that Hippolita should not part of the discussion, she quickly obeys.    Manfred, as villaince as he is, pleads with Friar to dissolve their marriage on the grounds that its was ill-contacted as Hippolita is his relative, but the Friar refuses to do. Hippolita comes up with a proposal to end the dead lock that fails to materialize. When Isabella protests about such proposal, she says to her:  \" Hold, you must not in my presence, young lady, mention Manfred with disrespect, he is my Lord and my husband\".    Hippolita is there till the very end to support Manfred when he is expelled from Otranto.    It is evident that the relationship between Manfred and his wife is strange and appears to be an unhappy on for Hippolita.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>1","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"1","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"The Blood of a Stranger by Dele Charley  How does the love for wealth and power influence the actions of the characters in the play?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Some of the character demonstrate love for money i.e greed and ambition throughout  the play whitehead, the whiteman and stranger, Maligu, the king's adviser, and Soko, the village shrine priest, are three of the characters that demonstrate the vice. Their sole objective is to get rich. whitehead  to  Mando  land intending to plunder the wealth of the people  and carry away their diamonds, under the pretext of Tobacco farming.       Greed sets in when Maligu and soko begin to lose trust in one another and plan to get rid of each other for the greater advantage of the diamond and wealth. The three want Kindo, the son of the king of Mando land and head of the Warriors, out of the way for them to succeed in their plan. Kindo recognizes it when he tells Maligu to \"pray for greed and ambition not to destroy\" him. Whitehead also wants Parker, an African who acts as his secretary and as assitant interpreter, and Soko did as they do not exactly fit into his plan beyond using them to acheive his aim. When Maligu stands the chance to save whitehead from death on his hands, he betrays him and simply thanks him for the diamond wealth that now apparently belongs to him alone.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>2","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"The Blood of a Stranger by Dele Charley  Assess Santigi's reign as king of Mando land","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Santigi  reigns in a  time of peace, the people of Mando land having come out of previous wars  with neighbouring tribes. Assisted  by Maligu his \"Wise counselor\" Soko, the priest, and his son who is chief of the Warriors, he appears  to be heading towards a quiet  and peaceful death in his dotage (old age).  However, santigi's kingdom is suddenly ruffled by the news of Soko's  contrived divination of a white stranger appearing  in the land. Aided and abetted by Maligu and Soko. the whiteman,symbolically, called Mr. whitehead, who has sent his messenger/secretary (interpreter...), Mr. Parker for (short) before him, appears, much against the custom of the people and does not  pay his respects to the king upom arrival, which is also against the custom. Kindo, the king's son, point this out, but his appeal is ignored  by the king who rigidly insists on things being done according to custom.    whitehead's arrival in  Mando land bodes no good for the people of Mando land under Santigi's reign. In complicity with Maligu and Soko, he deceive the king (urged on by Soko and Maligu)  that he brings  prosperity to Mando land through the introduction of tobacco farming, when his real diamond resources of the land, is never listened to by his father, the king.Thus, Santigi's reign is characterized by the violation of custom; for instance, the custom which forbid the people to smoke tobacco, alchohol and hard drugs, and as reported by Kindo, the men and women engage in sexual orgies, as societal norms and restrictions are abandoned \"in the name of happiness under the very eyes of Santigi\". A normally self-sustaining farming lose the will to work hard and embrace Laziness, rather.    Things do not improve, even at this stage, as whitehead and his accomplices, Maligu and Soko, single  out Kindo, the king's son, as the main obstacle of pursuing their greed for money and wealth. They hatch a plot which receives the king's support. To atone for the revival of  stranger  within, there should be a sacrfice involving  \"the blood of a stranger born in another place\". Soko interpretes this as being the blood of a virgin. Wara, Kindo's woman, is chosen. However, such is the distrust between the accomplices  that Soko spares Wara's life and on the day of the sacrifice, Kindo kills Parker, whitehead's secretary, who then become the sacrificial lamb.Santigi sit on his throne unaware of the demand of his custom and acquiesces to Wara being sacrificed instead. It takes Kindo to expose the grandf deception  and the killing of the whitehead to stop the descent into depravity that has engulfed the people.Ironically, Kindo's banishment is sanctioned by his own father, king Santigi, according to custom.    Here, therefore, is a king who, though old and insistent on tradition,has no high moral intergrity to show in his  violation for custom for money. Instead of protecting his people from outside negative influence, he superintends a corrupt and effete society whch is unlikely to improve under an equally  corrupt Maligu, if he should die and Kindo is unanle to return from banishment.    When it emerges that it is parker who has been sacrificed instead, whitehead calls for the enforcement of the tradition  which prescibes death for anybody who kills in peace time.whitehead in turn dies on Kindo's sword, accidentally.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>3","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"3","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"Harvest of Corruption by Frank Ogodo  Comment on the proceedings at the Wasa High Court of Justice","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Investigations into the activities of Chief Haladu Ade-Amaka are already in progress when Ogeyi goes to the police station on  account of her friend Aloho. Her story help the police to wrap up their investigation and prefer charges against Chief and five others, includind, Ochuole,at Wasa High Court of Justice presided over by the judge.    It appears that  only a fraction of the minister's sins against the state and some people is known. According to judge, \"for all the atrocities you must have perpetrated in this country under the cover of Minister, which have not been detected, i say nothing\" chief then faces  four counts of embezzlement, involving 1.2 billion naira and 5.8 million naira (two counts); dealing in cocaine and corrupting a public officer.    prosecution counsel clearly outlines the role of the police in their investigation and what makes each accused person culpable. Inspector Inaku evidence is claer and concise. What triggers police investigation is set down as \"Miss Ogeyi and the 'Jacassan Flash' of  21st june 1997\". Following the newspaper report, the inspector goes to the Ministry and bribes Mr Ayo to get acces to official documents. By the inspector's own    admission, Mr Ayo does not ask for a bribe; rather the clerical officer \"promised to cooperate after  i enticed him with the sum of two thousand naira\". This show of Zeal is wrong. The law seems to be that both the giver and the receiver of a bribe  are criminal, One would expect, then, that the court reprimand or even sentence Inspectore Inaku once Ayo goes in for five years.    In her evidence, Ogeyi  clearly  tells Aloho's story and firmly incriminates chief. Her reason for going to the police is conssistent with her love  for her later friend; failing to persuade Aloho not to abort the pregnancy, she \"was moved to go to the police to relate the story\". However, chief lies on oath, alleging that  the \"cocaine had been put there to incriminate\" him. In the end, the court does not believe him and his bfreaking down avails  him nothing. of the two, ogeyi is found credible by the court.    Both counsels do their work to the best of their abilities. Prosecution counsel notes  and draws attention  to Defence counsel's  \"clearly weaving  the evidence of the prosecution to confuse this honourable court \". He draws the court's attention to the relevant flaws in the case of the defence and leaves the rest to the judge and jury. The judge sums up succinctly and his guiding of the jury is balanced.    On the whole, the proceeding go well and the verdict arising from the evidence appears to be satisfactory.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>4","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"Harvest of Corruption by Frank Ogodo  Consider Aloho as a foil to Ogeyi","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Aloho and Ogeyi are friends from their universities days. They are both pretty, slim,and of average height. While Aloho is dark-shined, Ogeyi is fair. They are both born again christians.    Years after their graduation, Ogeyi secures a job with the ABC company as a recptionist,while Aloho is still searching for employment.Ogeyi, thou not that well off, is very benevolent.She does not accommodate and feed Aloho alone,she also encourages her to be patient and not lose faith in God.    When Aloho comes home with the promise of a \"bogus\" job by a notorious friend, Ogeyi counsels caution, but in Aloho's frustration and desperation,she flouts Ogeyi's advice and accepts the job of a protocol officer in the Ministry of External Relations.    Ogeyi does not give up in her preachings: she tries to dissuade Aloho, but her word fall on deaf ear as the glitter of the good life eggs Aloho on, Aloho soon find herself  in police custody for drugs traffkicking.    As soon as she is cleverly acquinted and discharge through the corrupt string-pulling of chief Ade- Amaka,Aloho discovers that she is pregnant. she attempt to abort the pregnancy but fails due to her nightmaish dream,Dr Chukwuma the gynaecologist's evasive delays tactics and Ogeyi fervent dissuasion.    In her cornered and remorseful situation, she finally returns to her family,but later dies in childbirth, through the baby survives.    Ogeyi launches into action to seek justice for her friend's death. she testifies boldly in court against  Chief Ade-Amaka, helping to bring him to his deserved \"harvest\".","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>5","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"5","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"A Raising in the Sun by Lorraibe Hansberry  What is the significance of karl Lindener's visits to the Youngers?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Karl Lindner is a whiteman. He visits the Youngers home twice  on the  same day, The purpose of his visit is to persuade the youngers not  to move into the house Mama has bought in clybourne park for the family.These visit are significant for understanding some aspects of the wolrl of the play.    The day Lindner goes to see the youngers they are preparing to move.\"The man\" meets Beneatha, Ruth and walter.Marna is out. Lindner's misson is simple:The cybourne Park improvement Association has sent him to let \"you people\" know that they do not want the younger family in the neighbourhood, for the whitemen there came from \" a common background \" in which  the youngers are unwanted aliens. He asasures Walter that \"overewhelming majority of our people out there  feel that people get along better, take more of a common interest in the life of the community when they share a common background\". For that reason, the whiteman wants \"to buy  the house from you at a financial gain of your family.\" The mission fails as Walter orders Lindner out of the house. As her goes out perflexed, Lindner leaves his card.    Lindner's second visit is at the invitation of Walter. Ostensibly, Walter wants to seal the deal of the sale of the house. But yhis does not happen. Walter has been inspired by his mother's fighting spirit to reject the offer of Lindner with finality.Lindner, of course, does not understand fully as he departs.    This visit are significant for understanding the Negro experience and the black-white relationship in America. Bobo's intervening report of the loss pof the family money that  Walter has handed over to Willy Harris for the Liquor business gives the family a philosophical outlook. Walter learns from hereand take the bold decision.it will be incompetent with the family's pride to agree sell house since \"ain't nobody in my family never let nobody pay 'em no money that was a way of telling us we wasn't fit to walk the earth\".This is how succintly Mama explains what Lindner seeks to do. Because \"we ain't never that poor\", the family must stict to its purpose and move into the new house. Mama is larger than life, as they say,and her stand establishes her as such.    The speed with which Walter picks the import of the philosophy is astonishing. This is a proud family and must hang on hope with tenacity. It is this that makes Walter decline Lindner's offers with finality  and for which Mama commeds Walter as having 'finallhy come into his manhood.'    Though Lindner protests that his visit  and Clybourne parkresidents' resistance to the yojungers family's  occupation of the poverty has no racial implications or racist undertones,that is not what the visit shows. The whiteman wishes to have little to do with the Negro as a neighbour.It is Lindner's  conviction and that of the white community in Clybourne part that  \"Our Negro familesare happierwhen they live in their own communities\".    Lindner's visits, therefore, reveal the reality of white rejection of Negroes as neighbours and the determination of the Negroes to improve the circumstances of their life at all cost.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>6","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"A Raising in the Sun by Lorraibe Hansberry  Trace the transformation of Walter \"into his manhood\" in the play","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Wallter, as a man should  have been head of the younger family. Yet, it is Mama who has been at the helm of affairs from the outset.Not satisfied with his situation in life, Walter is preoccupied with his dream of making it big,through the investment of money that is not his own. He dreams constantly of becoming a self-made man with the backing of his wife,while complainingh that no one understand him. Several he has proved a disappointment to Mama.    Uncaring about what goes on around him,Walter gets a good opportunity of showing himself as the worthy man his mother expects him to be when his wife decides to have an abortion. Typically, he is not even aware of his wife condition until Mama tells him.Mama urges him to take the bull by the horn and speak to his wife and talk her out of her decision. He falters in this and, bitterly disappointed, Mama calls him a \"disgrace to your father's memory\".    When George Murchison calls to take Beneatha out, Walter is inexplicably rude to the young man. He will not leave them alone despite Ruth's attempt to have him behave civily. George aptly describes him as \"all whacked up with bitterness\". On his part, Walter goes on about his vision and his being littlre understood.    Unable to see the wisdom in Mama's  buying the house with the insurance money,walter becomes bitter. He is rude at home and even absents himself at work. Hurt because his mother will not approve his liquor business intentions, he gets another chance to prove as the head of family \"like you supposed to be\", when Mama entrusts the remainder of the insurance money to him with specific instructions. Walker speedily goes and hands all of it over to Willy Harris who takes off  with the money.    The final opportunity to become the man he  should be comes when he rejects Lindner's offer to buy Mama's new  home. Bobo's report that Willy  has bolted with the money shows that the family has no more of the precious insurance money left. This makes the prospects of moving into 406 Clybourne street in the white neighbourhood of Clybourne park particularly bleak and precarious.    The man in Walter emerges, however and he invests Lindner over. Under a show of accepting the whiteman's offer to buy out the family, and contrary to the family's fears, he rejects the offer. He tells Lindner, \"we have decided to move into our house....don't want your money\". All this while, Mama has been showing her approval, as though she were in church with her head nodding the amen yes\"    Thus from a spineless dreamer and loafer, Walter transforms into a responsible head of the sixth generation younger family. Henceforth, things look secure in his hands.","marks":"25","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>7","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"7","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"She Stoops to Conquer by Oliver Goldsmith  Examine the importance of the jewels in the play","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The Jewels in the play refer to the box of jewels that is in Constance Neville's inheritance left in the care of Mrs. Hardcastle her aunt.    Mrs. Hardcastle does not wants to release the Jewels to the rightful owner, Constance. she intends to keep such inheritance in her family. Therefore, she cover up the intention by forcing Constance to marry Tony, mischievous son.    Constance is wise enough to play along with Mrs Hardcastle by letting her \"suppose that i am in love with her son and she never dreams that my affections are fixed upon another\".Hasting is the one Constance love and not Tony. Tony on his part, prefers Bet Bouncer to Constsnce. Because he is aware of his mother's plan to rob Constance of her inheritance,he agrees to be inlove with his cousin, Constance, in the presence of his materialistic mother.    Constance Neville is in no way ready to part with her inheritance as she confides in Hasting, her lover. So she pleads withj Hasting to bear with her until the moment the jewels are put into her hands; then their marriage can take place. The more Constance persuades her aunt to allow her access to the jewels, even if for a day, the more Mrs. Hardcastle insists on her marrying Tony.Meanwhile, Hasting discovers that truly Tony prefers Bet Bouncer to Constance. He therefore, persuades Tony to help steal the jewels from his mother.    Mrs. Hardcastle tells Tony to bear false witness before Constance, that the Jewels are missing. Ironically, the jewels are indeed missing because Tony has given then to Hasting to  help him elope with Constance. Hastings immediately gives the jewels to Young Marlow for safe keeping who, in turn gives them to Mrs. Hardcastle for safe-keeping too.    Tony informs his mother that the jewels are stolen, the mother then goes to check and discovers that the jewels are really missing, She raises an alarm that she's been robbed but Marlow tells her that the jewels are with him and gives her the jewels.    The jewels help to accentuate the irony, comedy,and indeed  the mistakes of the night in advancing the plot. Through the jewels, Hasting and Constance's plan of elopement is exposed. The jewels bring out the selfish and ,materialistic character of Mrs. Hardcastle.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>8","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"8","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN DRAMA","question":"She Stoops to Conquer by Oliver Goldsmith  Assess the role of Tony Lumpkin in the play","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Tony Lumpkin is  the older child in the Hardcastle family. He is Mrs. Hardcastle's child by her first marriage. He is a spoilt child, thanks  to his mother's permissive ways towards him. Obiviously Mr. Hardcastle would have been of help in bringing up Tony Lumpkin properly,but his wife will not allow it. He enjoys making practical jokes.    In the first place, Tony loves to spend his time among commoners in the village tavern. He is there when Young Marlow and Hasting come looking for there way to the Hardcastles. Tony takes this opportunity to take his stepfather back for calling him names all the time. He misdirects the visitors, describing the Hardcastle home as inn. This deception brings about exciting incidents in the plot. Young Marlow and Hastings go to the Hardcastle's house thinking it is an inn and the many mistakes of that night unfold, including the first meeting between Kate and Young Marlow.    Secondly, when Tony learns  that Hasting means to elope with his cousin,Miss Neville, whom his mother has been courting for him, he is more than stealing her jewels for her to enable her elope with Hastings.Tony succeed in doing this, and givers the jewels to Hasting who in turn give them to Marlow for safe keeping. Mistakenly, Marlow hands over the jewels to Mrs. Hardcastle. As a result  of this, Mrs Hardcastle decides Miss Neville must go live with aunt Pedigree at crackskul common.    Again it is Tony Lumpkin who comes to the rescue of the lover.He drives the carriage carrying his mother round and round pretending they are on the  way to Aunt Pedigree. They end up close to where they set out from and later Hastings has to make a formal proposal to Miss Neville to settle matters.    To conclude, Tony Lumpkin seems to be the pivot around which the plot of the comdey  develops. Anytime he appears, a new event begins or a situation is saved.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>9","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"9","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Examine the use of contrast in Okara's \"Piano and Drum\"","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Contrast is a device of juxtapose opposing idea or structures for effect. The poem makes use of extensive use of contrast to elucidate the theme of cultural difference between the Africa and the Western Culture.    The very title of the poem presents two contrasting musical instrument, a piano and drums. The former represents European culture whiles the latter, the African culture. The poet uses these contrasting musical instruments to comment on their effect on him. The drums are simple and easy to play. On the other hand, the  piano requires more effort to master. Auditory, the drum are \"pulsing\" while the  Piano \"wails\". The drum invoke memories of a past gone by- a past of \"hunters crouched with spears\" , a simple life filled with dances. The piano, on the other hand, speak of \"complex ways\", \"faraway lands\" and the poet  being \" lost in the labyrinth of its complexities\".    At the symbolic level, contrast is used as a device to shapen the differences between the cultures and to convey  the poet's  attitude towards both. Interestingly, the poet devotes the first two stanzas to drums while only one stanza is assigned to the piano. This contrast in  structure suggests his bias. It shows his sincere interest in the ways of his people. In each  stanza the poet examine the sound of the instrument and its effects on him,The piano is \"wailing\" and speaks of faraway lands\" and complex ways, none of which the poet deciphers, leaving him confused.    The last stanza portrays the poet as one caught between the influence of the two cultures. However, the force of the drums seems overwhelming and tilts him towards the African culture.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>10","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"10","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Comment on the mood of the poet in \"Ambush\"","images":[],"marking_scheme":"\"Ambush\" portrays a society under siege. The Isolation of the people pre-empts or prosperity. The powers-that-be appear to hold their subject in a vice like grip.    By the use of powerful imagery and symbols the poet unveils his mood of despondency in his deprived and gloomy circumstances.  This is also the mood of the citizens of the land, who, individually and collectively, are denied any means or opportunities of improving their lot.  By whatever means imaginable( by sea,land,or air) various agents, allices of \"the land\" (the autocracy) reinforce  the deprivation of the people. The people's  means of livelihood is obliterated;they are  frightened and intimidated; their very existence is threatened. Above all, they dare not seek relief outside the land.    Through the metaphor of the \"giant whale\", the poets conveys the miserable picture of the people's chances of earning any livelihood being put paid to. The image of angling conveys this vividly, for the land swallows the angler's hook, line and sinker thus \"aborting dreams of a  good catch\".    Thus the people are bereft of hope and expectation as their desires dwindle. The metaphor of the sea serves to convey the harsh restriction imposed  on the people. The people are also held in terror unleashe by another agent of the \"land\" by land. The frightful tiger keeps the whole population in  fear. None is exempted: both the old and the    young dare not exhibit any bravo, nor venture out at night. \"This is how the \"land\" denies the people any escape by land.     The function of the agents that hovers overhead is to heighten the people's and invite chaos on  them. The hawk continuosly \"courts\" ruin of the land with its \"hoots in space\". The impossibility of attempting to escape without being picked up is made certain by the hawk's  presence.    Matters are sealed for the poor masses as local forces are harnessed and the \"land lies patiently ahead/awaiting in ambush\" for its own kith and kin. The purpose of the ambush is not to pritects the people from invaders.Rather, it is to frustrate any attempt to escape for relief elsewhere. In the homeland, \"where nothing happens\", the signs of want are apparent and the people need to migrate \"toward the shore of possibilities\", But they dare not.    The hopeless and frustrating circumstances of the poet make him utterly exasperated and depressed. Thus the mood of hopelessness and frustration permates the poem.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>11","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"11","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN POETRY","question":"How does the poet present death as a voyage in \"Crossing the Bar\"?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"In the poem, death is presented as the end of life on earth and the start of man's return to his maker. The metaphor of a voyage appropriately  describes this transition.    The symbol marking the end of life are \"sunset and evening star\". These constitutes \"one clear call for me\". Thus the persona knows when his life has come to an end and he  needs  only to embark gladly on the voyage home. Death, therefore, is not to be feared .    The barrier between the mortal world and the world of eternity is human body. This is represented by the sand bar. At death, one's spirit leaves the mortal body and is free to go \"home\". Without death the spirit is not freed to set off. This makes death inevitable.    Death is described as the final extinguishing of the light of life. It is when the light s gone that one sets out to board the eternity-bound vessel. This is captured succinctly as:                             \"Twilight and evening bell                           And after that the dar\".  The symbols appropriately echo the earlier symbols marking the end of life:                                       \"sunset and evening star                          And after that the dark\"    The certainty of death and the obvious final signposts  are clearly  put down in the poem. After death, the spirit is transported  across the waves  as it \"turns again home\". On crossing the bar, the spirit passenger boards the ship and must be introduced  to the captain , that is, \"see my pilot face to face\".    The prospect of death and actually dying are not frightful, sorrowful or regrettable. They are all in the scheme of our mortality. As for the persona, he can take these in hs stride. However, his  experience has been that survivors do mourn for the dead. This is not necessary. He urges  survivors of the dead  thus:                             \"And may there be no sadness of farewell                             When i embark\".    His hope, which is almost a certainty, is that, when he has \"crost the bar\" (died), he will be quite safe meeting his \"pilot\" who will take him to his destination, however far it s  and however long the voyage lasts.    Through effective metaphors and imaginary, death is presented as the inevitable close of the chapter of living on earth and the opening of the way...\"again home\".","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Literature>2018>Paper III>12","subject":"Literature","year":"2018","type":"Theory","sub_label":"12","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"NON-AFRICAN POETRY","question":"Examine Blake's use of diction in the \"School Boy\"","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Regardng theme, the poem deals with the restrictons imposed by adults on children's natural freedom, as these stifle their natural growth  and development. Blake  uses te natural ryhthm of speech to convey this theme, particularly as he allows the boy to express himself in his own languagge,as much as possible. Apart from the rhymed stanzas, most of the lines read like colloquial speech. The following examples illustrates the point. In stanza one, the boy express his love for summer in the word: \"i loveto rise on a summer mourn\". Then, In stanza two, he expresses his unhappines about going to   school in the line, \"Oh it drives all joy away\". Many more lines are couched in such monosyllabic words.    In additon to the above expressions , it can be said that the very words used in the poem are simple. Indeed the longest word used the entire poem is \"mellowing\" which is made up of three syllables. Words associated with spring and summer are used to describes the season positively.    They include \"sing\",\"joy\", \"sweet company\", \"blossom\" and so on.The focus of the poem being summer, such words expresses the boy's delight in being associated with his activities. Similarly in referring to spring time, he refers to \"buds\" and \"blossom\". However,words associated with school do not have positive association. In school the boys tasks about \"singing\"and \"dismay\", and \"drooping\". The teachers are \"cruel eye outworn\" and school, which should be a \"learning's bower\" has become a \"dreary shower\" . The boy associates his misery with that of a \"bird caged\" and unable to \"sing\" or with  that of a tender plant that has been \"stripped\" of its leaves, or with that of \"buds\" that have been nipped before they blossom.    Indeed there are many more negative words and expressions in the poem. These illustrates the boy's melancholic mood as he laments his inability to enjoy summer  because of the insensitivity of his parents to his feelings and natural inclinations by sending him to school. However, beyond this meaning is one larger, which is the need to give children opportunity to be self  expressive, so they can psychologically withstand the crisis of adulthood. it is to the poet's credit  that such profound wisdom is conveyed in the simplicity of the vocabulary or diction.","marks":"25","difficulty":"2"}];